# AD User Audit Tool

## Overview
This PowerShell script audits Active Directory user accounts and exports important account information into a CSV report.

The report helps administrators review:
- Enabled accounts
- Last logon activity
- Password last set date
- Account creation date
- Inactive users

## Features
- Export AD user information to CSV
- Calculate inactive days automatically
- Simple and easy-to-read output
- Supports single-domain environments
- Lightweight script with minimal configuration

## Requirements
- Windows PowerShell 5.1 or later
- Active Directory PowerShell Module
- Domain-connected machine
- Read access to Active Directory

## Usage

Run the script from PowerShell:

```powershell
.\AD-User-Audit.ps1
```

## Output File

The script generates:

```txt
AD_User_Audit_Report.csv
```

## Example CSV Output

| DisplayName | SamAccountName | Enabled | PasswordLastSet | LastLogonDate | InactiveDays |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| John Doe | jdoe | True | 05-01-2026 | 10-05-2026 | 3 |
| Sarah Smith | ssmith | True | 12-12-2025 | 01-01-2026 | 132 |
| Test User | tuser | False | 20-11-2025 |  | Never Logged In |

## Example Use Cases
- AD account auditing
- Security review preparation
- Identifying inactive accounts
- User activity reporting
- Internal compliance checks

## Domain Scope

This script is designed for single-domain Active Directory environments.

It targets the domain of the machine/server where the script is executed.

## Notes
- Test the script in a lab environment before production use
- Some accounts may show blank LastLogonDate if they never logged in
- CSV output can be opened directly in Microsoft Excel

